-----------------------
---- DOS EXTENDERS ----
-----------------------

The following DOS-Extender environments are supported with Zinc
Application Framework 3.5:

- Borland C++ 3.1 and Phar Lap 286|DOS-Extender 2.5 with the GFX
  graphics library
- Borland C++ 3.1 and Phar Lap 286|DOS-Extender 2.5 with the BGI
  graphics library
- Microsoft C/C++ 7.0 and Phar Lap 286|DOS-Extender 2.5 with the GFX
  graphics library
- Microsoft C/C++ 7.0 and Phar Lap 286|DOS-Extender 2.5 with the MSC
  graphics library
- Zortech C++ 3.1 and the Zortech Z-model 16-bit DOS-
  Extender with the GFX graphics library
- Zortech C++ 3.1 and the Zortech Z-model 16-bit DOS-
  Extender with the FG graphics library
- Zortech C++ 3.1 (NOT 3.0) and the Zortech X-model 32-bit DOS-
  Extender with the GFX graphics library (Requires patch in
  SOURCE\Z32MOUSE.  See note below under ---- Zortech ----)
- Zortech C++ 3.1 (NOT 3.0) and the Zortech X-model 32-bit DOS-
  Extender with the FG graphics library (Requires patch in
  SOURCE\Z32MOUSE.  See note below under ---- Zortech ----)

The following sections describe how to configure your computer for
use with DOS-Extenders and how to build aplications with DOS-
Extenders.  Each section discusses a specific compiler.

------------------------
---- VIRTUAL MEMORY ----
------------------------

The following virtual memory environments are supported with Zinc
Application Framework 3.5:

- Borland C++ 3.1 and Borland VROOM with the GFX graphics library
- Borland C++ 3.1 and Borland VROOM with the BGI graphics library
- Borland C++ 3.1 and RTLink 5.20 with the GFX graphics library
- Microsoft C/C++ 7.0 Microsoft MOVE with the GFX graphics 
  library
- Microsoft C/C++ 7.0 Microsoft MOVE with the MSC graphics 
  library


---- Borland ----

Building protected mode applications with the Borland compiler can
only be done using a makefile or the command-line compiler and linker.
The makefile template below shows the options and settings that should
be used when building applications with the Phar Lap DOS-Extender.  
Please note that the order of the LIBs is very important.

# --- Use for PharLap Extended programs. ---
CPP16=bcc286
D16_LINK=tlink

D16_CPP_OPTS=-c -ml -O -w
D16_LINK_OPTS=/c /C /x

D16_OBJS=c0pl
# --- Use the next line for UI_GRAPHICS_DISPLAY ---
D16_LIBS=phapi d16_zil d16_gfx bc_16gfx emu286 emu mathl bcl286
# --- Use the next line for UI_BGI_DISPLAY ---
#D16_LIBS=phapi d16_zil d16_bgi graph286 emu286 emu mathl bcl286

.cpp.o16:
       $(CPP16) $(D16_CPP_OPTS) -o$*.o16 {$< }

D16_BIND=bind286
PHARLAP_RTL=c:\pharlap\rtk
D16_LOAD=run286a

prog16.exe: prog.o16
       $(D16_LINK) $(D16_LINK_OPTS) @&&!
$(D16_OBJS)+prog.o16
$*, , $(D16_LIBS),bprog16.def
!
      $(D16_BIND) @$$!
$(PHARLAP_RTL)\$(D16_LOAD)
$*
-dll $(PHARLAP_RTL)\moucalls
     $(PHARLAP_RTL)\int33
     $(PHARLAP_RTL)\doscalls

The module definition file (bprog16.def in the example above) must 
contain the following information:

PROTMODE
STUB 'gorun286.exe'
EXPORTS BCC286_EXE

The environment's LIB and INCLUDE variables must be set to include a
path to the Phar Lap directories that contain Borland support files.
Please refer to the Phar Lap documentation for more help on configuring
your environment for the Phar Lap DOS-Extender.

The environment's PATH variable must have paths to the Phar Lap BIN 
directory and also to the Borland BIN directory so that the various
compilers and linkers can be invoked.

The Borland TURBOC.CFG and TLINK.CFG files must also be modified to 
include paths to the Zinc libraries and include files.


---- Microsoft ----

Building protected mode applications with the Microsoft compiler can 
be done using either the PWB or a makefile.  The makefile template
below shows the options and settings that should be used when building
applications with the Phar Lap DOS-Extender.  Please note that the
order of the LIBs is very important.

# --- Use for PharLap Extended programs. ---
D16_CPP=cl
D16_LINK=link

D16_CPP_OPTS=-c -AL -BATCH -Gs2 -nologo -DDOSX286 
D16_LINK_OPTS=/NOD /NOI /BATCH /SEGMENTS:256 /STACK:8192 /FAR

# --- Use the next line for UI_GRAPHICS_DISPLAY ---
D16_OBJS=graphp.obj
D16_LIBS=phapi d16_zil d16_gfx ms_16gfx llibcep graphics oldnames
# --- Use the next lines for UI_MSC_DISPLAY ---
#D16_OBJS=graphp.obj
#D16_LIBS=phapi d16_zil d16_msc llibcep graphics oldnames

D16_BIND=bind286
PHARLAP_RTL=c:\pharlap\rtk
D16_LOAD=run286a

.cpp.o16:
      $(D16_CPP) $(D16_CPP_OPTS) -Fo$*.o16 $<

prog16.exe: prog.o16
       $(D16_LINK) $(D16_LINK_OPTS) @<<zil.rsp
$(D16_OBJS)+prog.o16
$*,NUL,$(D16_LIBS),NUL
<<
      $(D16_BIND) @<<zil.rsp
$(PHARLAP_RTL)\$(D16_LOAD)
$*
-dll $(PHARLAP_RTL)\moucalls
     $(PHARLAP_RTL)\int33
     $(PHARLAP_RTL)\doscalls
<<
      @del zil.rsp

The environment's LIB and INCLUDE variables must be set to include a
path to the Phar Lap directories that contain Microsoft support files
and also to the Microsoft LIB and INCLUDE directories.  Please refer
to the Phar Lap documentation for more help on configuring your 
environment for the Phar Lap DOS-Extender.  

The environment's PATH variable must have paths to the Phar Lap BIN
directory and also to the Microsoft BIN directory so that the various
compilers and linkers can be invoked.


---- Zortech ----

Building protected mode applications with the Zortech compiler can be
done using either the ZWB or a makefile.  The makefile template below
shows the options and settings that should be used when building
applications with the Zortech DOS-Extender.  Please note that the
order of the LIBs is very important.

NOTE: Zortech 32-bit X-model library ZPS.LIB contains a bug with the
      mouse support.  A .OBJ file with the correction has been
      included in SOURCE\Z32MOUSE.  You should either link this file
      in explicitly, before ZPS.LIB or, update ZPS.LIB.  

# ----- 16-bit DOS extender compiler options ------------------------
D16_CPP=ztc
D16_LINK=blinkx

D16_CPP_OPTS=-c -bx -mz -D$(FONT)
D16_LINK_OPTS=/NOI

D16_OBJS=
# --- Use the next line for UI_GRAPHICS_DISPLAY ---
#D16_LIBS=zpm d16_zil d16_gfx zt_16gfx
# --- Use the next line for UI_FG_DISPLAY ---
D16_LIBS=zpm d16_zil d16_fg fg

.cpp.o16:
       $(D16_CPP) $(D16_CPP_OPTS) -o$@ $<

# ----- 32-bit DOS extender compiler options ------------------------
D32_CPP=ztc
D32_LINK=blinkx

D32_CPP_OPTS=-c -bx -mx -D$(FONT)
D32_LINK_OPTS=/NOI

D32_OBJS=cx
# --- Use the next line for UI_GRAPHICS_DISPLAY ---
#D32_LIBS=d32_zil d32_gfx zt_32gfx
# --- Use the next line for UI_FG_DISPLAY ---
D32_LIBS=d32_zil d32_fg fgp

.cpp.o32:
       $(D32_CPP) $(D32_CPP_OPTS) -o$@ $<

prog16.exe: prog.o16
       $(D16_LINK) $(D16_LINK_OPTS) $(D16_OBJS)+prog.o16, $*, , $(D16_LIBS),
zprog16.def

prog32.exe: prog.o32
       $(D32_LINK) $(D32_LINK_OPTS) $(D32_OBJS)+prog.o32, $*, , $(D32_LIBS),
zprog32.def

